    <exploration>
      <statement>
        As it turns out, we can also use matrices to describe linear transformations between non-euclidean spaces using <term>coordinates</term>. Let's see how using differentiation <m>D: \mathbb{P}_2 \to \mathbb{P}_2</m> of quadratic polynomials as an example.
        
        <ol>
          <li>Consider the general quadratic <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>. Why can the subspace <m>\mathbb{P}_2</m> of quadratics be represented by the basis <m>\mathcal{B}=\{x^2, x, 1\}</m>?</li>
          <li>What is the image under <m>D</m> of each of the basis vectors?</li>
          <li>Under the basis <m>\mathcal{B}</m>, what is the coordinate vector that describes a general quadratic?</li>
